 Testing Approach
Unit Testing
Unit tests were written for core calculation functions(profit calculation, stock level updates, tax application) and utility functions (formatters, validators).

Integration Testing
Integration tests covered critical flows like :creating a product, then selling it, and verifying that the stock level decreased correctly and the sale appears in the report.

User Acceptance Testing (UAT)
UAT was conducted with a local kirana(grocery) store owner .Feedback was collected on the sales interface speed, clarity of the low-stock alerts, and the usefulness of the Profit & Loss report.
Challenges Faced

Real-Time Stock Update Integrity
Challenge :Ensuring that simultaneous sales of the same product (a rare but possible scenario) do not cause a "race condition" where stock levels become incorrect.
Solution: Implemented database transactions and "pessimistic locking" during the sale process to ensure that stock updates are atomic and sequential.

 Performance with Large Product Lists
Challenge  :The product search during sales needed to be instantaneous, even with a catalog of several thousand products.
Solution:I implemented client-side debouncing on the search input and used efficient database indexing on the product name and  columns.

Learnings & Key Takeaways

 Technical Learnings
Database Transactions are Critical :For financial and inventory data, using transactions is non-negotiable to maintain data integrity.
UI/UX for Speed :For business software, especially used in customer-facing scenarios, UI speed and efficiency are as important as features.

Domain Learnings
Understanding Retail Workflows :Spending time with retailers to understand their daily routine (peak hours, common operations) was invaluable in designing the right user flows.
The Value of Simplicity :The most successful feature was the simple low-stock alert. Solving a single, painful problem effectively can provide immense value.
